Rating: 4
Well, I messed up and forgot to prepare this the night before, but it still came out fabulously and I thought I'd share in case anyone else finds themself in the same predicament. I also weighed my bread - seems to me part of the reason for the differing degrees of sogginess is at least in part to blame for their rather vague description of how much bread to use. Anyway, I used 10.25 ounces of bread, cut into about 18 pieces about 1 inch thick. Since I did not have very long to soak the bread, I cut the milk back to 2 cups. I let the bread soak for 3 hours, then I turned the bread over (to help speed the soaking process) and let it sit out and come to room temperature (cold pyrex in hot oven=big mess). I also cut back on one dirty dish by roasting the pecans on my stovetop - I added the butter and salt after about 5 minutes of roasting and stirred until the butter was melted. This turned out wonderfully. Nice and rich without being too rich - I think whole milk is essential for added flavor and richness. I baked it at 400 for about 25 minutes.It was not soggy at all - just perfect. We also skipped the syrup - you don't really need any, but I drizzle of plain maple syrup is very nice. So, if you forget to prepare it the night before, you can still have it easily ready in time for a late brunch.

